---
import TopRoastersLayout from '../../layouts/TopRoastersLayout.astro';
export const prerender = true;

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "Is Nashville a legitimate specialty coffee city?",
    a: "Absolutely. Nashville's coffee scene went from strip mall chains to a serious specialty market in under a decade, driven by a wave of hospitality investment and a growing population of food-literate residents. Roasters like Barista Parlor and Stay Golden earned national recognition, and the wholesale market followed. Today Nashville supports more legitimate specialty wholesale volume than cities twice its historical reputation."
  },
  {
    q: "Which Nashville roasters have wholesale programs?",
    a: "8th & Roast has one of the most developed wholesale programs in the Southeast, having expanded nationally through its acquisition of Good Citizen Coffee Co. Crema Coffee Roasters, Frothy Monkey Roasting Co., and Honest Coffee Roasters all run active wholesale programs for café and restaurant accounts. The Well Coffee Roasters serves mission-aligned wholesale buyers."
  },
  {
    q: "How does Nashville's growth affect coffee wholesale?",
    a: "Nashville's hotel and restaurant boom created enormous wholesale demand. The expansion of convention hotels, boutique hospitality properties, and restaurant groups created accounts that specialty roasters were well-positioned to serve. 8th & Roast's presence in Nashville International Airport is a direct result of that hospitality growth. For roasters, Nashville's momentum is an ongoing opportunity."
  },
  {
    q: "What coffee origins do Nashville roasters favor?",
    a: "Nashville roasters broadly favor Central American and East African origins, which align with the region's preference for clean, bright cup profiles. Crema and 8th & Roast source extensively from Colombia and Guatemala. Barista Parlor and Stay Golden lean toward Ethiopia and Kenya for their single-origin menus. Honest Coffee Roasters focuses on direct relationships with Latin American producers."
  }
];
---

<TopRoastersLayout
  title="The 7 Best Specialty Coffee Roasters in Nashville"
  description="Nashville's coffee scene grew up fast, and the roasters who built it are serious. A guide to the city's best specialty roasters — their sourcing, their wholesale programs, and what makes each one worth knowing."
  city="Nashville"
  slug="nashville"
  roasterCount={7}
  publishDate="2024-06-01"
  updatedDate="2025-03-15"
  {faqItems}
>

  <p class="body-text">
    Nashville arrived late to specialty coffee and didn't apologize about it. In the span of about eight years, the city went from a market dominated by national chains to one that supports nationally recognized independent roasters, an active barista competition scene, and wholesale demand strong enough to support multiple roasters running serious production capacity.
  </p>
  <p class="body-text">
    What drove it was the hospitality boom — hotels, restaurants, event venues — and a transplant population with already-developed coffee preferences. The roasters that planted flags early are now among the region's best. What follows is the ones worth knowing.
  </p>

  <div class="roaster-card">
    <span class="roaster-number">01 / 07</span>
    <h2 class="roaster-name">8th & Roast</h2>
    <div class="roaster-tagline">8th Ave South, Charlotte Ave, Midtown &amp; Nashville International Airport · Founded 2008</div>
    <div class="roaster-body">
      <p>8th & Roast is the closest thing Nashville has to an institutional coffee brand, and unlike most institutional brands, the coffee has stayed excellent. Founded in 2008 and acquired in 2016 by Ed and Sam Reed alongside co-owner Q-Juan Taylor, the roastery has grown into a multi-location operation with airport presence, a national wholesale program, and a 2024 acquisition of Good Citizen Coffee Co. that expanded both their team and their customer base.</p>
      <p>The Good Citizen acquisition was strategic: Good Citizen had built accounts at properties including the Downtown Embassy Suites, Grand Hyatt Nashville, Union Station Hotel, and other major hospitality venues. 8th & Roast absorbed that book of business and the Good Citizen and Common Voice coffee lines alongside it.</p>
      <p>For wholesale buyers across the Southeast, 8th & Roast is the most accessible entry point into Nashville-roasted specialty coffee — with five retail locations, a national shipping infrastructure, and a wholesale team that's practiced at onboarding new accounts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="roaster-tags">
      <span class="roaster-tag">Southeast Leader</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Wholesale National</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Hospitality Accounts</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Airport Presence</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="roaster-card">
    <span class="roaster-number">02 / 07</span>
    <h2 class="roaster-name">Barista Parlor</h2>
    <div class="roaster-tagline">East Nashville, Germantown &amp; multiple locations · Founded 2011</div>
    <div class="roaster-body">
      <p>Barista Parlor opened in East Nashville in 2011 in a space that felt like a deliberate statement — industrial fixtures, reclaimed wood, an espresso bar positioned like a performance stage. The aesthetic was intentional and ahead of the curve, but the coffee had to back it up. It did. Founder Andy Mumma sourced with precision, and the bar program became a training ground for some of Nashville's best baristas.</p>
      <p>The aesthetic influence spread further than Nashville — Barista Parlor's design language shaped how dozens of cafés across the South understood what a serious specialty coffee bar should look like. That cultural capital translates directly to wholesale: partnering with Barista Parlor communicates something to guests before they take a sip.</p>
      <p>Their single-origin program leans Ethiopian and Kenyan, with seasonal rotating lots that give wholesale partners a reason to update their menus quarterly. Wholesale accounts get direct access to the sourcing team for education support.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="roaster-tags">
      <span class="roaster-tag">Design-Forward</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">East African Origins</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Wholesale</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Barista Education</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="roaster-card">
    <span class="roaster-number">03 / 07</span>
    <h2 class="roaster-name">Crema Coffee Roasters</h2>
    <div class="roaster-tagline">Downtown Nashville · Founded 2011</div>
    <div class="roaster-body">
      <p>Crema opened in 2011 in a downtown Nashville space that felt too quiet for the location — and that quietude was the point. Co-founders Jared Linzmeier and Jeremy Stangroom built a café focused on technique: precision extraction, water chemistry dialing, seasonal single-origins presented as carefully as a wine program. The bar became a destination for people who wanted coffee to be taken seriously.</p>
      <p>Crema's wholesale program reflects that philosophy. They're deliberate about which accounts they take on — looking for operators who want to engage with the product rather than just source a commodity. For the right buyer, that relationship translates into ongoing sourcing education, barista certification, and a quarterly cupping program that keeps palates sharp.</p>
      <p>Their sourcing emphasizes Colombia, Guatemala, and East Africa. The Costa Rica Chacon Black Diamond Roaster Series — with its raspberry, dark brownie, and rooibos tea notes — is a flagship that wholesale buyers have consistently featured as a menu anchor.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="roaster-tags">
      <span class="roaster-tag">Technique-Forward</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Colombian Origins</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Wholesale</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Roaster Series</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="roaster-card">
    <span class="roaster-number">04 / 07</span>
    <h2 class="roaster-name">Honest Coffee Roasters</h2>
    <div class="roaster-tagline">Nashville (multiple locations) · Founded 2013</div>
    <div class="roaster-body">
      <p>The name is the brief. Honest Coffee Roasters was built on the premise that most of the opacity in coffee's supply chain is unnecessary — and that direct relationships with producers are better for quality, for farmers, and for the people drinking the cup. Their sourcing runs through Latin America, with deep relationships in Guatemala and Honduras.</p>
      <p>The wholesale program emphasizes transparency: every offering comes with producer information, altitude, processing method, and cupping notes that give café teams something real to talk to guests about. That documentation is part of what wholesale partners are buying — not just coffee, but a story they can tell with confidence.</p>
      <p>Well-suited for restaurant accounts and café operators who want their coffee program to reflect intentionality, not just quality.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="roaster-tags">
      <span class="roaster-tag">Direct Trade</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Latin American Origins</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Wholesale</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Transparent Sourcing</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="roaster-card">
    <span class="roaster-number">05 / 07</span>
    <h2 class="roaster-name">Stay Golden Restaurant &amp; Roastery</h2>
    <div class="roaster-tagline">Nashville · Founded 2014</div>
    <div class="roaster-body">
      <p>Stay Golden operates at the intersection of food and coffee culture in a way that most roasters don't attempt. The restaurant and roastery share a space that functions as one program — the sourcing philosophy for the coffee informs the beverage pairing for the menu, and vice versa. That integration makes Stay Golden particularly compelling for wholesale buyers in the hospitality sector, where coffee often needs to coexist with a broader culinary vision.</p>
      <p>Co-founders Erin Scott and Nick Terzis have built a sourcing program that emphasizes process experimentation — honey, anaerobic, and natural lots make regular appearances on the menu alongside washed classics. Wholesale partners get seasonal cupping events and hands-on sessions that treat coffee education as ongoing rather than one-time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="roaster-tags">
      <span class="roaster-tag">Restaurant Integration</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Process Experimentation</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Wholesale</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Seasonal Cuppings</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="roaster-card">
    <span class="roaster-number">06 / 07</span>
    <h2 class="roaster-name">Frothy Monkey Roasting Co.</h2>
    <div class="roaster-tagline">Nashville (multiple locations) · Founded 2004</div>
    <div class="roaster-body">
      <p>Frothy Monkey predates the specialty wave in Nashville, which gives the brand something most newer roasters can't manufacture: genuine neighborhood credibility. The original 12South location opened in 2004 when the neighborhood was still quiet, and the café became part of the community before community coffee culture was a business strategy.</p>
      <p>The roasting side has evolved to match the specialty market. Free-trade sourcing, small-batch roasting, and a subscription program that ships nationally sit alongside a café operation that still feels like it belongs to the block. Wholesale offerings range from house blends suited to high-volume café settings to seasonal single-origin offerings for more curated programs.</p>
      <p>Howler Espresso — a Brazilian and Central American blend with red grape, almond butter, and dark chocolate notes — is a perennial wholesale favorite for cafés running high espresso volume.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="roaster-tags">
      <span class="roaster-tag">Neighborhood Institution</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Free Trade</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Wholesale</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Espresso Program</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="roaster-card">
    <span class="roaster-number">07 / 07</span>
    <h2 class="roaster-name">The Well Coffee Roasters</h2>
    <div class="roaster-tagline">Nashville (multiple locations) · Founded 2012</div>
    <div class="roaster-body">
      <p>The Well's mission statement — Turning Coffee Into Water — is not marketing language. Since 2012, the roastery has channeled a portion of every sale into funding clean water projects in coffee-producing regions. That mission has created an unusually loyal customer base and a wholesale profile that resonates with mission-aligned buyers: nonprofits, faith communities, cause-driven businesses.</p>
      <p>The coffee program doesn't lean on the mission to cover for the cup quality. Sourcing is meticulous, small-batch roasting is the standard, and new packaging introduced in 2024 tells each coffee's origin story through the visual design. Wholesale partners in the 12oz, 2lb, and 5lb formats get that story told on the bag, which makes shelf presence and counter presence genuinely differentiating.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="roaster-tags">
      <span class="roaster-tag">Mission-Driven</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Clean Water Initiative</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Wholesale</span>
      <span class="roaster-tag">Small Batch</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="section-header">Nashville Coffee: <em>What's Driving It</em></h2>
  <p class="body-text">
    Nashville's hospitality sector is one of the fastest-growing in the country, and specialty coffee followed the restaurants and hotels in. The city now supports enough wholesale volume to sustain roasters at serious production scale — 8th & Roast's acquisition of Good Citizen was a direct signal that the market had matured enough to reward consolidation.
  </p>
  <p class="body-text">
    For wholesale buyers in Tennessee and the broader Southeast, the roasters on this list represent a genuinely competitive market for specialty quality. Any one of them would make a credible anchor for a serious coffee program.
  </p>

